FINETUNED MODEL INTEGRATION — SUMMARY
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
WHAT WE BUILT
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

A dual-model detection pipeline that runs a general YOLO26m model
alongside a finetuned model, merges their detections intelligently,
and feeds the result into a single tracker.

The finetuned model detects two domain-specific classes that the
general model cannot reliably distinguish:
  - soldier  (appears as person in general model)
  - barrier  (appears as car / truck / bus etc in general model)


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 1 — CONDITIONAL INFERENCE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The finetuned model is expensive to run. We only run it when the
general model detects something that could be a soldier or barrier.

  - General model always runs first
  - If no soldier or barrier detected → return general results only
  - If soldier or barrier detected → also run finetuned model

This means on most frames only one model runs. The finetuned model
is only triggered when relevant.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 2 — SEPARATE INFERENCE PARAMETERS PER MODEL
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each model has tuned parameters because they serve different roles:

  General model:   conf=0.25, imgsz=640
                   YOLO26 is NMS-free so iou= has no effect

  Finetuned model: conf=0.35, imgsz=640, iou=0.5
                   Higher conf threshold — domain model should be
                   more certain. Lower NMS iou — soldiers and
                   barriers can be dense, avoid merging close boxes.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 3 — RECONCILIATION (THE CORE PROBLEM)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

After both models run, the same physical object may have been
detected by both. We need to decide: same object or different?

We compare every (finetuned box, general box) pair using three
geometric signals:

  IoU — how much do the boxes overlap relative to their combined
        area. Strong signal when boxes are similar in size.

  IoF — symmetric intersection over foreground. Measures what
        fraction of one box is covered by the other, in both
        directions, taking the max. Catches containment when one
        box is much smaller than the other (e.g. cone inside truck
        box, or tight person box inside loose soldier box).

  Center check — is the finetuned box center inside the general
        box? Tiebreaker that prevents false conflicts between
        adjacent objects whose edges touch but are separate things.

Decision order:
  1. IoU above threshold → conflict confirmed
  2. IoF above threshold AND center inside → conflict confirmed
  3. Otherwise → different objects, keep both


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 4 — CONFLICT RULES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Different object pairs need different thresholds and resolution
strategies because their geometry and semantics differ.

soldier vs person     iou=0.5  iof=0.7  strategy=always_finetuned
  A soldier is a person. Boxes should be nearly identical.
  High thresholds because a soldier NEXT TO a civilian should not
  trigger a conflict. Finetuned always wins — the label is more
  specific, not contradictory. Confidence is irrelevant.

barrier vs anything   iou=0.3  iof=0.6  strategy=highest_conf
  Barrier covers many shapes — cones, wide barriers, checkpoints,
  jersey blocks. Boxes are inconsistent so thresholds are lower.
  Neither label has inherent priority — a truck could genuinely
  be there, or a barrier could. Highest confidence wins.

Rules are built programmatically so adding a new general class
only requires adding it to COCO_NAMES — no manual rule needed.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 5 — STRATEGIES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Resolution strategies are defined as a dict of functions so:
  - All valid strategies are visible in one place
  - A typo raises an immediate error rather than silent failure
  - Adding a new strategy never requires changing reconcile()

  always_finetuned  suppress general detection unconditionally
  highest_conf      suppress whichever detection has lower score


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 6 — SINGLE TRACKER ON MERGED OUTPUT
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Running one tracker per model causes two problems:
  - Same physical object gets two track IDs
  - When reconciliation suppresses one box, that track ID dies
    and the other takes over — the tracker sees a false new object

Solution: run one single BoTSORT tracker on the merged detections
after reconciliation. One object → one box → one stable ID.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STEP 7 — LABEL MEMORY
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The finetuned model only runs on some frames. When it does not
run, a soldier track would revert to the person label — the label
flips every time finetuned triggers or does not trigger.

Solution: once a track is assigned a finetuned label at high
confidence (≥ 0.6), lock that label to the track ID. The label
stays stable even on frames where finetuned does not run.

The confidence threshold prevents the label memory from being
assigned to the wrong track after a tracker ID switch — a low
confidence detection near an occlusion is more likely to be a
tracking error than a genuine new soldier detection.

Label memory is cleared when a track dies to avoid stale entries.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
KEY DESIGN DECISIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Finetuned only runs when triggered
    Avoids double inference on every frame. Cost is paid only
    when soldier or barrier is actually present.

  Finetuned always wins for soldier
    A soldier is semantically a superset of person. The specific
    label always carries more information than the general one
    regardless of confidence scores.

  Highest confidence wins for barrier
    Barrier and vehicle are genuinely different object types.
    Neither label has inherent priority so confidence is used
    as a proxy for which model is more certain.

  Symmetric IoF instead of one-directional
    Either model can draw a larger box depending on the object.
    Taking the max of both directions catches containment
    regardless of which box is bigger.

  Center check as tiebreaker
    Shape-agnostic. A real adjacent object will have its center
    outside the neighbouring box even if edges touch. Prevents
    false conflicts between separate objects near each other.

  Single tracker
    Ensures one ID per physical object across all frames
    regardless of which model detected it.

  Label memory with confidence gate
    Stabilises labels across frames without risking permanent
    mislabelling after tracker ID switches under occlusion.


───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
FILE STRUCTURE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  constants.py    COCO class definitions, trigger labels,
                  conflict rules, thresholds. Pure data only.

  strategies.py   Strategy functions and STRATEGIES dict.
                  All conflict resolution logic.

  geometry.py     IoU, IoF, center check, is_conflict().
                  Pure box math, no side effects.

  utils.py        Video utilities — fps, metadata, frame count.
                  Generic helpers unrelated to detection logic.

  detector.py     Main pipeline — inference, reconciliation,
                  tracking, label memory. Imports from all above.

